01:40.042 --> 01:44.170
"The same lack of integrity to cause so
many people to take the easy way out...

01:44.338 --> 01:47.173
...was rapidly turning the town
of his dreams..."

01:47.341 --> 01:51.636
No, it's gonna be too preachy. I mean,
face it, I wanna sell some books here.

01:51.803 --> 01:54.597
"Chapter one. He adored New York City...

01:54.765 --> 01:59.143
...although to him it was a metaphor
for the decay of contemporary culture."

01:59.311 --> 02:04.649
"How hard it was to exist in a society
desensitized by drugs, loud music...

02:04.816 --> 02:07.610
...television, crime, garbage..."

02:07.778 --> 02:09.946
Too angry. I don't wanna be angry.

02:10.113 --> 02:12.406
"Chapter one."

02:12.574 --> 02:15.576
"He was as tough and romantic
as the city he loved."

02:15.744 --> 02:19.038
"Behind his black-rimmed glasses
was the coiled sexual power

02:19.207 --> 02:20.457
of a jungle cat."

02:20.625 --> 02:22.167
I love this.

02:22.335 --> 02:25.754
"New York was his town
and it always would be."

04:20.997 --> 04:26.919
I think the essence of art is to provide
a kind of working-through situation...

04:27.087 --> 04:30.589
...so that you can get in touch
with feelings you didn't know you had.

04:30.757 --> 04:35.052
Talent is luck.
The important thing in life is courage.

04:35.220 --> 04:37.221
They've had this argument
for 20 years.

04:37.388 --> 04:39.473
Listen to this example.

04:39.641 --> 04:44.561
If the four of us are walking home over
the bridge and a person was drowning...

04:44.729 --> 04:46.730
...would we have the nerve...

04:46.898 --> 04:50.692
Would one of us have the nerve to dive
into the icy water and save them?

04:50.860 --> 04:52.653
It's a key question.

04:52.821 --> 04:55.656
I, of course, can't swim,
so I never have to face it.

04:56.491 --> 04:58.575
Oh... God.

04:59.202 --> 05:01.286
Which of us?

05:02.413 --> 05:05.040
- You want a little more?
- No.

05:05.208 --> 05:09.003
Mm. Oh, man. That is so great.

05:09.171 --> 05:10.964
You don't smoke.

05:11.132 --> 05:15.718
I know I don't smoke. I don't inhale
because it gives you cancer, but...

05:16.137 --> 05:21.266
...I look so incredibly handsome with
a cigarette that I can't not hold one.

05:22.852 --> 05:24.853
- You like the way I look?
- Mm-hm.

05:25.020 --> 05:26.396
Provocative.

05:26.564 --> 05:30.525
- I'm getting through to you?
- Yup. You have to excuse me a sec.

05:31.694 --> 05:35.029
- Jesus, she's gorgeous.
- Mm.

05:35.906 --> 05:37.991
But she's 17.

05:38.325 --> 05:40.410
I'm 42 and she's 17.

05:41.245 --> 05:45.540
I'm... I'm older than her father.
Can you believe that?

05:46.041 --> 05:49.043
I'm dating a girl
wherein I can beat up her father.

05:49.211 --> 05:52.172
That's the first time
that ever occurred in my life.

05:52.339 --> 05:56.551
- He's drunk.
- You're drunk. You should never drink.

05:56.719 --> 06:00.263
Did I tell you... that my ex-wife...

06:00.431 --> 06:04.184
- Who, Tina?
- Mm-mm. My second ex-wife...

06:05.020 --> 06:08.063
...is writing a book about
our marriage and the break-up.

06:08.231 --> 06:11.442
- That's really tacky.
- It's really depressing, you know.

06:11.610 --> 06:16.197
She's gonna give all those details out,
all my little idiosyncrasies...

06:16.364 --> 06:18.824
...and my quirks and mannerisms, and...

06:18.992 --> 06:22.828
Mm, mm, not that I have
anything to hide because, you know...

06:22.996 --> 06:27.499
But there are a few disgusting
little moments that I regret.

06:27.667 --> 06:30.544
It's just gossip.
Gossip is the new pornography.

06:30.712 --> 06:34.173
- You should never let me drink.
- I know.

06:34.341 --> 06:36.550
You should never let yourself drink.

06:36.718 --> 06:39.345
We oughta go
'cause I've got an exam tomorrow.

06:39.512 --> 06:42.014
Oh, do you? The kid's gotta get up...

06:44.142 --> 06:47.186
She's got homework.
I'm dating a girl who does homework.

06:48.480 --> 06:50.689
What is it? What's the matter with you?

06:50.857 --> 06:54.818
You... you... Where are you now?
Your mind is like a million miles away.

06:54.986 --> 06:56.987
I have something I wanna say.

06:57.155 --> 07:00.032
I, uh, I just didn't know
quite how to... get into it.

07:00.200 --> 07:02.285
Um, I, uh...

07:03.120 --> 07:07.499
About seven or eight weeks ago
I went to this dinner party...

07:07.667 --> 07:09.751
...and I met a woman there.

07:10.461 --> 07:12.754
And...

07:12.922 --> 07:16.258
And I've got
kind of involved with her.

07:16.425 --> 07:17.509
You're kidding?

07:17.677 --> 07:21.346
It started out very casually.
I mean, we had lunch a couple of times.

07:21.514 --> 07:23.014
And now it's, you know,

07:23.182 --> 07:25.934
it's getting out of hand
and I don't know what to do about it.

07:26.102 --> 07:28.186
I mean, I'm... It's scary.

07:28.354 --> 07:31.356
Well, who is she? What are the details?

07:31.524 --> 07:33.692
- Well, she's a journalist.
- Uh-huh.

07:33.859 --> 07:35.443
She's very...

07:35.611 --> 07:38.029
- Is she married, too?
- No, no.

07:38.197 --> 07:40.448
- She's very beautiful.
- Mm-mm.

07:40.616 --> 07:44.577
She's very kind of
nervous, high-strung, illusive.

07:44.745 --> 07:47.163
Great. It sounds wonderful.

07:47.331 --> 07:51.668
Oh, she is wonderful.
I mean, she's on my mind all the time.

07:51.836 --> 07:54.921
What are you telling me?
That your marriage is...

07:55.089 --> 07:58.718
I mean, how serious is it?

07:58.885 --> 08:01.345
I don't know, but it's pretty serious.

08:01.513 --> 08:03.347
But you haven't
said anything to Emily?

08:03.515 --> 08:05.057
No! God, no.

08:05.225 --> 08:08.686
It's amazing. I'm stunned
because, of all the people I know...

08:08.854 --> 08:12.940
...I always thought for sure that you
and Emily had one of the best marriages.

08:13.108 --> 08:15.443
We do! I mean, I love her.

08:15.610 --> 08:17.987
- But you're seeing...
- I know it.

08:18.155 --> 08:20.906
But in all the years
that we've been married...

08:21.074 --> 08:25.286
...I've had, what... one or two
very minor things with other women.

08:25.454 --> 08:28.622
I mean, very... I hate the whole idea.

08:28.790 --> 08:31.375
I hate myself
when I'm doing this sort of thing.

08:31.543 --> 08:34.587
But this is just, you know...
This is not like that.

08:34.755 --> 08:38.174
It's terrible. Listen,
you shouldn't ask me for advice.

08:38.342 --> 08:43.346
When it comes to relationships, I'm the
winner of the August Strindberg Award.

08:43.513 --> 08:48.100
Well, I don't think 17 is too young.
Beside that, she's a bright girl.

08:48.268 --> 08:51.604
You'll get no argument from me.
I think she's terrific.

08:51.772 --> 08:54.983
He could do a lot worse.
He has done a lot worse.

08:55.151 --> 08:57.361
I just think he's wasting his life.

08:57.528 --> 09:00.655
He writes that crap for television.

09:02.075 --> 09:05.660
Yale, have you ever thought
any more about having kids?

09:06.537 --> 09:08.622
Oh, my God. Kids.

09:08.790 --> 09:12.667
Listen, I've gotta get this book
finished. It's never gonna get done.

09:12.835 --> 09:16.129
I've gotta get the money
to get this magazine started, huh?

09:16.297 --> 09:17.881
Kids...

09:18.049 --> 09:21.676
We always talk about moving to
Connecticut. You could do it there.

09:21.844 --> 09:24.262
- Connecticut.
- Yeah.

09:24.430 --> 09:27.641
I can't go to Connecticut.
It's not practical.

09:27.809 --> 09:29.810
All my stuff's here.

09:29.977 --> 09:32.437
My work's here.
It's just the wrong time.

09:32.605 --> 09:36.066
What about Isaac?
We can't abandon him, you know?

09:36.234 --> 09:40.237
He can't function anywhere
other than New York, you know that.

09:40.405 --> 09:42.489
Very Freudian.

09:43.699 --> 09:45.992
Mm-mm...

10:00.092 --> 10:02.343
Are you writing a book
on our marriage?

10:02.511 --> 10:03.594
Leave me alone.

10:03.762 --> 10:07.849
- Are you writing about our break-up?
- We've said all that needs to be said.

10:08.016 --> 10:10.852
I know you are because
I have a friend at Random House.

10:11.019 --> 10:14.272
- I'm free to do as I please.
- Yeah, but this affects me.

10:14.440 --> 10:18.109
So you're gonna tell everybody
everything? Our life, our sexual life?

10:18.277 --> 10:19.652
Do you spy on me?

10:19.820 --> 10:23.448
No. I was at a party and a guy said
he read an advance chapter...

10:23.615 --> 10:27.326
...of a book my wife was writing,
and it was hot stuff. He said that!

10:27.494 --> 10:31.372
- I spilled wine on my pants.
- I don't care to discuss it.

10:31.540 --> 10:34.041
- You won't discuss it. How's Willie?
- Fine.

10:34.209 --> 10:38.546
Well, give me some details. Does he
play baseball? Wear dresses? What?

10:38.714 --> 10:40.715
He doesn't wear dresses.

10:40.883 --> 10:43.551
You'll find out the details
when it's your turn to see him.

10:43.719 --> 10:46.345
Don't write this book.
It's a humiliating experience.

10:46.513 --> 10:48.807
It's an honest account of our break-up.

10:48.975 --> 10:52.144
Jesus, everybody that knows us
is gonna know everything.

10:52.312 --> 10:54.521
Look at you. You're so threatened.

10:54.689 --> 10:59.651
I'm not threatened because I was not
the immoral, psychotic, promiscuous one.

10:59.819 --> 11:02.196
I hope I didn't leave out anything.

11:07.911 --> 11:12.956
Are you telling me that... that I'm...
that you had three affairs before me?

11:13.124 --> 11:16.585
That's really hard to believe.
It's mind-boggling.

11:16.753 --> 11:20.839
When I was your age, I was still being
tucked in by my grandparents.

11:21.007 --> 11:25.135
Well, they were really immature boys.
They were nothing like you.

11:25.303 --> 11:27.304
No? What does that mean?

11:27.472 --> 11:30.557
Well, I told you before.
I think I'm in love with you.

11:30.725 --> 11:32.976
Hey, don't get carried away, OK?

11:33.144 --> 11:36.647
This is... This is a terrific thing -
move over - you know.

11:36.814 --> 11:40.400
And we're having a great time,
but you're a kid

11:40.568 --> 11:42.694
and I never want you to forget that.

11:42.862 --> 11:45.532
You're gonna meet
a lot of terrific men in your life...

11:45.699 --> 11:47.825
...and, you know,
I want you to enjoy me.

11:47.993 --> 11:52.038
My wry sense of humor
And astonishing sexual technique...

11:52.206 --> 11:56.209
...but never forget that you've...
you've got your whole life ahead of you.

11:56.377 --> 11:58.545
Don't you have any feelings for me?

11:58.712 --> 12:02.257
How can you ask that?
I've got nothing but feelings for you...

12:02.424 --> 12:06.052
...but you don't wanna get hung up
with one person at your age.

12:06.220 --> 12:09.389
It's... charming, you know.

12:09.557 --> 12:12.475
Erotic.
No question about that.

12:12.643 --> 12:14.727
As long as the cops don't burst in,

12:14.895 --> 12:17.105
I think we're gonna break
a couple of records.

12:17.273 --> 12:20.608
But you can't, uh, you can't...
It's not a good thing.

12:20.776 --> 12:25.071
You should think of me sort of
as a detour on the highway of life.

12:25.239 --> 12:28.866
- So get dressed because you gotta go.
- Don't you want me to stay over?

12:29.034 --> 12:31.244
I don't want you to get in the habit...

12:31.412 --> 12:33.997
...because first you stay one night,
then two nights,

12:34.164 --> 12:36.416
and then you're living here.

12:36.584 --> 12:39.252
- That doesn't sound too bad.
- It's not a great idea.

12:39.420 --> 12:42.923
You won't like it, believe me.
I'm tough to get along with.

12:43.091 --> 12:47.928
Tomorrow we'll go to the cinema and I'll
show you the Veronica Lake movie. OK?

12:48.096 --> 12:51.724
OK. Veronica Lake's
the pin-up with the red hair?

12:51.891 --> 12:55.769
No, that's Rita Hayworth.
Do we have to go over this all the time?

12:55.937 --> 12:59.690
- Rita who?
- Rita Hayworth. Are you joking with me?

12:59.858 --> 13:04.653
Course I'm joking! You think I'm unaware
of any event pre-Paul McCartney.

13:07.240 --> 13:10.451
- I find these photographs interesting.
- Yes, so do I.

13:10.619 --> 13:14.246
- Do you ever use the camera I got you?
- Oh, yeah, I use it all the time.

13:14.414 --> 13:18.042
I was taking pictures in our drama
class. It's fun, really neat.

13:18.209 --> 13:21.003
You know you sound like
the mouse in Tom And Jerry.

13:21.171 --> 13:22.546
Are you kidding me?

13:22.714 --> 13:26.258
- You should talk! You've a whiny voice!
- Sh! You sound like the mouse.

13:26.426 --> 13:28.218
Well, thanks.

13:28.386 --> 13:31.555
I know, I'm a whiner.

13:33.099 --> 13:35.851
- What are you doing here?
- Hi.

13:36.019 --> 13:38.938
- How long have you been here?
- We were talking about you.

13:39.106 --> 13:43.526
That's hilarious. Wh... What... Were you
walking around behind us or what?

13:43.694 --> 13:46.905
- How are you? Hi.
- Good. That's funny. We were talking...

13:47.073 --> 13:49.991
We're gonna go to
the Shakespeare In The Park thing.

13:50.159 --> 13:52.160
Oh, yeah, right. I wanna do that.

13:52.328 --> 13:55.872
Oh, this is my friend.
Mary Wilke, Isaac Davis and Tracy.

13:56.040 --> 13:58.083
- How do you do?
- Hi. Nice to meet you.

13:58.250 --> 13:59.501
You, too.

13:59.669 --> 14:01.252
- Hello.
- Hi.

14:01.420 --> 14:04.422
We were downstairs.
We saw the photography exhibition.

14:04.590 --> 14:07.175
- Absolutely incredible.
- It's really good.

14:07.343 --> 14:08.760
Really?

14:08.928 --> 14:11.513
- The photographs downstairs?
- Yes.

14:11.681 --> 14:14.516
Great. Absolutely great. Did you?

14:14.684 --> 14:16.810
No, I really felt
it was very derivative.

14:16.977 --> 14:19.354
To me it looked like it was
straight out of Diane Arbus,

14:19.522 --> 14:21.481
but it had none of the wit.

14:21.649 --> 14:25.318
Well, we didn't like it
as much as the Plexiglas sculpture.

14:25.486 --> 14:27.237
You liked the Plexiglas?

14:27.405 --> 14:29.781
You didn't like the Plexiglas either?

14:29.949 --> 14:33.494
Ah, that's interesting.
Nah, no... uh-uh.

14:33.662 --> 14:37.164
It was a lot better than that...
that steel cube. Did you see it?

14:37.332 --> 14:41.377
- Oh, yeah. That was the worst.
- Now that was brilliant to me.

14:41.545 --> 14:43.546
- The cube was brilliant?
- Yes.

14:43.714 --> 14:46.757
To me it was very textural.
You know what I mean?

14:46.925 --> 14:49.552
It was perfectly integrated
and it had a...

14:49.720 --> 14:51.637
a marvelous kind of negative capability.

14:51.805 --> 14:53.889
The rest of the stuff was bullshit.

14:57.936 --> 15:00.771
- You wanna see the Sol Lewitt?
- Sure. That'd be fun.

15:00.939 --> 15:02.314
You wanna see that?

15:02.482 --> 15:05.985
He opens at the Modern soon. I was
gonna do a piece on Sol for Insights.

15:06.153 --> 15:09.071
Do you know that magazine?
It's a little magazine.

15:09.239 --> 15:13.325
They're such schmucks up there.
Really mired in Thirties radicalism.

15:13.493 --> 15:15.828
- What do you do, Tracy?
- I go to high school.

15:15.996 --> 15:21.000
Oh, really. Really. Somewhere Nabokov
is smiling, if you know what I mean.

15:21.877 --> 15:25.504
LeWitt is overrated. In fact,
he may be a candidate for the academy.

15:25.672 --> 15:26.964
Right!

15:27.132 --> 15:31.344
Mary and I have invented the Academy
of the Overrated for such notables as...

15:31.512 --> 15:34.639
...Gustav Mahler...
- Isak Dinesen and Carl Jung.

15:34.807 --> 15:38.268
...Scott Fitzgerald.
- Lenny Bruce. Can't forget him, can we?

15:38.436 --> 15:42.189
- How about Norman Mailer?
- I think those people are all terrific.

15:42.356 --> 15:46.067
- Who was that guy you had?
- I didn't. It was yours. Heinrich BÃ¶ll.

